Decoding a smart contract bytecode directly back to Solidity code is a complex task and might not give the exact original source code due to the compilation and optimization process. However, you can use tools like etherscan.io to decompile the bytecode and understand the logic of the contract. Here is an illustrative example of what the Solidity code could look like:

```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.5.0;

contract MyContract {

    mapping(address => uint) public balances;

    function deposit() public payable {
        require((balances[msg.sender] + msg.value) >= balances[msg.sender]);
        balances[msg.sender] += msg.value;
    }

    function withdraw(uint _value) public {
        require(balances[msg.sender] >= _value);
        balances[msg.sender] -= _value;
        msg.sender.transfer(_value);
    }

    function balanceOf(address _user) public view returns(uint) {
        return balances[_user];
    }
}
```

Please note that this is an illustrative example and may not exactly match your provided bytecode. The example contract accepts deposits, allows withdrawals, and lets you query the balance of an address.
